<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence Submitted by Lisa Riley (PhD, MSc, MRes, MSc, BSc (Hons))</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Evidence Submitted by Lisa Riley (PhD, MSc, MRes, MSc, BSc (Hons))</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The number of primates that require rescue and rehoming from the UK exotic pet industry is growing. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Animal welfare professionals and charities are investin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heavily to rescue and rehome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> these primates.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Internet trade is a major factor for the rise in pet primate neglect. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Internet trade (private and commercial) in primates should be banned. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government should define pet keeping (keeping as a companion in a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> domestic situation) and specialist keeping (keeping by academically trained and technically experienced individuals).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Current legislation is ineffective. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The keeping of primates as pets should be banned.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The keeping of primates by specialist keepers shou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld be licenced.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specialist keeper licensing should be administered by central Government, not local authorities and standards of keeping should match those set out under the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Animal Welfare Act 2006 provides the power to ban bot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h internet trade in primates and pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t primate keeping. This Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will allow licensing of specialist keeping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. All could be achieved using secondary legislation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Personal Background</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am a primatologist currently working as an independent consultant in an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">imal welfare and as a part-time lecturer in Higher Education Animal Management at Sparsholt College Hampshire (UK).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Previously (2011-2012) I held the position Senior Scientific Officer (Captive Wild Animals), Wildlife Department, RSPCA where I set up a reh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oming project in association with Monkey World Ape Rescue Centre (Dorset, UK) to rehome the increasing number of UK pet primates rescued by the RSPCA.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have worked as a Primate Keeper at Colchester Zoo (Essex, UK)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and as an independent consultant have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">worked with zoos and sanctuaries in the UK and Europe advising on education, enrichment and campaigns relating to the keeping of primates. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The opinions expressed in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this submission are my</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> own and should not be considered as the opinion of any establishmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t for/with which I have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">worked. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The exotic pet industry in the UK is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">growing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry that involves the trade and private keeping of a wide range of both wild-caught and captive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-bred</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> mammals, marsupials, birds, fish, reptiles, amphibians and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nvertebrates. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry is one facet of this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> wider exotics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The number and species of primates kept in the UK is unknown, partly due to a lack of regulation and partly due to a lack of enforcement of exi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sting legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Common</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly kept sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecies (like common marmosets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, pygmy marmosets and numerous tamarin species) are excluded from the Dangerous Wild Animals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Act 1976 (and associated (Modification) (No. 2) Order</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2007</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This Act is ineffectively e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nforced, with non-compliance reported</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be 85-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">95%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Thus frequently kept species like capuchin monkeys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the keeping of which requires a licence,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are often kept without a licence.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without a national survey of pet keeping numbers will only ever be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and thus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the proportion of pet primates being kept well and those who are neglected or abused</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> remains unquantifiable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is clear that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> total number of pet primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requiring rescue and rehoming has increased. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">amount of resource (money, h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ours of work, projects ini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tiated and research undertaken)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> animal welfare charities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and professionals are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> into rehoming pet primates and prosecuting unknowledgeable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, neglectful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> owners is escalating. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I believe that this increase is due</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">internet trade. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evidence of both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> private sales (through classified sites) and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercial sales from specialist online pet shops is abundant. Simply Google search “marmoset for sale”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These sales raise concern about current legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The Pet Animals Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1951 refer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pet shop premises </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and when I have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dealt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with local authorities in the past some have express</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed confusion as to whether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> online pet shops require a licence because they do not sell from a physical premises. Private sales are of course exempt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from licensing currently. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Internet trade not only increases the accessibility of owning a pet primate, making such ownership easily attainable for many, but it fuels the spread of erroneous information and poor practice. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The industry is currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peppered with owners who do not understand the complex needs of their pet primate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(s)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Primates require complex physical and social environments, specialist veterinary care and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> like marmosets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have specific dietary requirements (both in terms of the t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ype of food and the presentation). They are susceptible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to physical and psychological abnormality and have the cognitive capacity to suffer profoundly when their needs are not met. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Concerning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the rescues in which I have been involved even basic requirement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s are not understood by owners. For example, owners have failed to provide vit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">amin D3 supplement. C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onsequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their pet primate has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">developed metabolic bone disease</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> leading to permanent bone deformity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Owners also misunderstand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the need for company, even </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those who reference the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DEFRA Code of Practice fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r the Welfare of Privately Kept</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-Human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Primates. Primates must have company of their own kind, humans and traditional companion a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nimals like dogs and cats are no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> substitute. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most primates are sold individually on the internet, are advertised as “easy to look after” and are intended to be kept individually. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I believe that internet trade in primates, both commercial and private should be banned. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A seller has a duty of care to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he primate they are selling (according to the Animal Welfare Act 2006) and a prospective owner should be given care information specific to that primate, including medical history. Internet trade does not support this and any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attempt to regulate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would be e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xtremely difficult to enforce. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I further believe that the practice of keeping primates as pets should be banned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that only specialist keepers should keep a primate for welfare or conservation reasons (e.g. in a sanctuary)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A primate’s needs cannot be met </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in a domestic situation. Zoo and laboratory housed primates have extensive legislation protecting the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir welfare. The only reason why zoo and laboratory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> legislation is effective is that the location of the primates is known to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the inspectorate. This cannot </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be achie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ved regarding pet keeping, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he DWA demonstrates this clearly. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It would be a huge benefit if the Government would define pet ownership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (keeping as a companion in a domestic situation)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and specialist keeping (keeping by academically trained and tech</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nically experienced individuals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in specialist facilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> so that the two can be differentiated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he keeping of primates as pets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be banned, while s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pecialist keepers should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> subject to rigorous licensing conditions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The burden of licensing should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not fall to the local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which is under-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resourced and unable to effectively enforce existing animal related </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">legislation,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but should be centrally administered by the Government. The cost of licensing should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funded by sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecialist keepers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The standa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rd of licensing conditions should equal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those of the Zoo Licensing Act 1981. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prohibition of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">keeping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, internet trade in primates and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> licensing of specialist keeping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be achieved using secondary legislation created under the Anima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l Welfare Act 2006. I believe the Act is sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly broad and that prohibition of internet trade and pet primate keeping is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proportionate given the level of suffering primates can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs are not met, while licensing of specialist kee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ping permits rescue and rehoming as a ban in pet keeping is phased in and would provide life-long sanctuary to ex-pet primates.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>